ation, on self-editing, and on how not to be “difficult.” Saller’s own gaffes provide firsthand (and sometimes humorous) examples of exactly what not to do. The revised content reflects today’s publishing practices while retaining the self-deprecating tone and sharp humor that helped make the first edition so popular. Saller maintains that through carefulness, transparency, and flexibility, editors can build trust and cooperation with writers. The Subversive Copy Editor brings a refreshingly levelheaded approach to the classic battle between writers and editors. This sage advice will prove useful and entertaining to anyone charged with the sometimes perilous task of improving the writing of others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCopy editing. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aadvice, manual, guidebook, handbook, chicago, relationships, interpersonal, communication, writers, authors, publishing, colleagues, work, workplace, shop talk, style, manuscript, editor, editorial, guru, prose, styling, reader, copy, grammar, contemporary, modern, current, up to date, publication, formatting, cooperation, discussion, chapter, professional.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226240107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226240107/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles